Insert into GAMETRACE.GAME (GAMEID,GAMENAME,GAMEPC,GAMERY,GAMEPSEC,GAMEPMIN,GAMEPHOUR,GAMEPDAY,GAMEPN,GIMG,GAMEDR,GAMEDESC,GAMEICON) values (532,'Rise of Nations',0,2003,0,0,0,0,0,'../../games/532.jpg','<game>
	<rule>
		<proc>nations.exe</proc>
		<file>taunts.txt</file>
	</rule>
</game> ','The core of Rise of Nations''s gameplay centers around the concept of "territory". The area near the player''s settlements is considered their territory, and players may only construct buildings within their territory or that of an ally. A nation''s borders can be expanded by the creation and expansion of cities and forts, a technology tree, and obtaining access to certain rare resources. Other technologies and resources cause enemy units within a nation''s borders to suffer attrition over time, which can eventually destroy an unsupplied invasion force.

Citizens in Rise of Nations gather resources, or build or repair damaged buildings. All of the six resource types in Rise of Nations are infinite in supply.

Any of the game''s nations can be played during any age, regardless of that nation''s fate throughout actual history. Each of the 18 civilizations in Rise of Nations has 4 to 8 unique units. Some unique units are based on units that those nations would have, if they were not destroyed in real-life. For example, the Native American nations (the Aztecs, Maya, and Inca) have unique units in the Modern and Information ages which resemble real-world Iberian-South American guerrillas. There are 4 end conditions: capture, territorial superiority, wonder victory, or score victory.','../../icons/532.png');
Insert into GAMETRACE.GAME (GAMEID,GAMENAME,GAMEPC,GAMERY,GAMEPSEC,GAMEPMIN,GAMEPHOUR,GAMEPDAY,GAMEPN,GIMG,GAMEDR,GAMEDESC,GAMEICON) values (534,'Command ' || chr(38) || ' Conquer: Red Alert 3',0,2008,0,0,0,0,0,'../../games/534.jpg','<game>
